If you ain’t ever lived paycheck to paycheck you wouldn’t understand.  Most of these executive and defense attorney have not and they don’t.  But here’s the reality. 

When you get your money is as important as getting the money.  The law in New York requires some workers to be paid every week, and if they were not, they can file a claim for anytime they were paid late in the past 6 years.

Section 190(4) of the New York State Labor Law defines a “manual worker” as “a mechanic, workingman or laborer.” It has been the long-standing interpretation of the NY Department of Labor that individuals who spend more than 25% of working time engaged in “physical labor” fit within the meaning of the term “manual worker.” Furthermore, the term “physical labor” has been interpreted broadly to include countless physical tasks performed by employees.

Labor Law Section 191 outlines the frequency by which employees must be paid.

Manual Workers: Wages must be paid weekly and not later than seven calendar days after the end of the week in which the wages are earned. 

Manual workers for non- profit entities must be paid in accordance with their agreed terms of employment but not less frequently than semi-monthly. Large employers of manual workers may apply to the Commissioner of Labor to pay manual workers semi-monthly.

The Supreme Court has sent a message to all workers paid on a day rate basis that they are entitled to overtime after 40 hours of work.

In a 6-3 ruling Wednesday, the Supreme Court noted that the case hinged on the issue of whether Hewitt, whose job is called tool pusher, was paid on a salary basis.

The majority opinion, written by Justice Elena Kagan, noted that Hewitt’s bi-weekly paycheck amounted to his daily pay rate multiplied by the number of days he worked in the pay period.

“The question here is whether a high-earning employee is compensated on a ‘salary basis’ when his paycheck is based solely on a daily rate — so that he receives a certain amount if he works one day in a week, twice as much for two days, three times as much for three, and so on,” wrote Kagan.

The New York City Fair Workweek Law, which was implemented in November 2017, aimed to give workers in certain industries, including fast food, more predictability in their schedules. For Fast Food workers, this includes:

1. **Advanced Notice of Work Schedules:** Employers are required to provide workers with their work schedules at least 14 days in advance. If changes are made to the schedule within this 14-day period, the employer may have to pay the worker a schedule change premium.

2. **Right to Rest:** Fast food workers have the right to decline any shift that starts less than 11 hours after the end of their previous day’s shift. If they agree to work during this period, their employer must pay them a $100 premium for the shift. N.Y.C. Admin. Code § 20-1231; 6 R.C.N.Y. § 7-601(a).

There are MANY MANY more requirements and rights for employees.  To find out more, and learn if we can bring a claim on your behalf against a current or former employer, contact us at 833-PAY-FAIR, that’s 833-729-3247 or send DM.

Attorney Advertising

Under New York State Labor Law, contractors and subcontractors must pay the prevailing rate of wage and supplements (fringe benefits) to all workers under a public work contract. Employers must pay the prevailing wage rate set for the locality where the work is performed. Prevailing wage is the pay rate set by law for work on public work projects. This applies to all laborers, workers or mechanics employed under a public work contract. The Bureau of Public Work administers Articles 8 and 9 of the New York State Labor Laws:

Article 8 covers public construction
Article 9 covers building service contracts
We issue wage schedules on a county-by-county basis. They contain the pay rates for each work classification. Under State law, all contracts between a government entity and a contractor must contain these schedules.

The prevailing wage law for building service workers amends Public Service Law Article 2 (Section 42-A). The law now requires that the wages and benefits of building service employees at active major electric or steam-generating facilities, or at transmission or distribution facilities considered critical infrastructure as determined by the NYS Division Homeland Security and Emergency Services (DHSES), in consultation with the NYS Department of Public Service (DPS), will be subject to Labor Law Article 9 prevailing wage requirements. This new law went into effect on September 30, 2020.

There are MANY MANY more requirements and rights for employees.  To find out more, and learn if we can bring a claim on your behalf against a current or former employer, contact us at 833-PAY-FAIR, that’s 833-729-3247 or send DM.

The New York City Fair Workweek Law, which was implemented in November 2017, aimed to give workers in certain industries, including fast food, more predictability in their schedules. For Fast Food workers, this includes:

1. **Advanced Notice of Work Schedules:** Employers are required to provide workers with their work schedules at least 14 days in advance. If changes are made to the schedule within this 14-day period, the employer may have to pay the worker a schedule change premium.

2. **Right to Rest:** Fast food workers have the right to decline any shift that starts less than 11 hours after the end of their previous day’s shift. If they agree to work during this period, their employer must pay them a $100 premium for the shift. N.Y.C. Admin. Code § 20-1231; 6 R.C.N.Y. § 7-601(a).

There are MANY MANY more requirements and rights for employees.  To find out more, and learn if we can bring a claim on your behalf against a current or former employer, contact us at 833-PAY-FAIR, that’s 833-729-3247 or send DM.

Intentional infliction of emotional distress (IIED) is a legal concept that refers to the deliberate and extreme conduct of an individual or entity, resulting in severe emotional suffering or distress to another person. It typically involves intentional actions or behavior that go beyond what is considered acceptable in society, causing the victim to experience significant psychological harm. The conduct must be intentional, outrageous, and beyond the bounds of what a reasonable person should endure. Keep in mind that laws and specific definitions may vary depending on the jurisdiction.
